description:
1 fighting spear and scabbard.  

A. wood, metal. Long wooden shaft. A section of the shaft near the point is covered over with metal that has two decorative bands. A second, smaller section of metal goes around the shaft at the very end, perhaps serving as a ferrule to strenghten the connection between shaft and blade. The blade, point has a shaft base that widens in to the blade prop? The blade tapers to a point, is sharp on both sides and has a raised midline.  


B. sheath. Wood, rattan. Sheath made of 2 identical carved halves that come together to form a complete item. Sharpened like the blade of A. with one end open. The other is closed and rounded off. 3 strips of interwoven rattan hold the 2 parts of wood together near the open end. Lightweight wood. Measures 42 by 7 by 4.;

Shield shaped in a long, narrow hexagon with the short edges slightly concave. Both sides are painted with black, white and red patterns. The black patterns are floral/ abstract. The front has fanged faces and possibly other patterns obscured by hair. 

Most of the front is covered in sections of black hair (uncertain if animal or human). Near the ends of the long sides of the hexagon, there are cross-pieces made of rattan- both ends, both sides. 

The back also has a carved wooden handle. There is also a section of fiber cord attached to the rattan on one end of the back.;

1 bamboo carrying tube ("Cawit") for coconut sap and attached brush no. 8404. 


For carrying tuba from tree to house.  Made for collection. 


Section of bamboo -- outer surface worked into round tube with flat surface along one side and facets near top ground entire tube.  At faceted section a long curved handle is attached and held in place by woven fiber -- rattan or wicker.  Another braid of this fiber near top has a loop for attaching 8404.;

1 knife, used in peeling culms 


Pan Lapat Tagalog 


Slightly curved steel blade set in wood handle.  Handle is wrapped with plant fiber.;

1 awl used in making hats 


Pan Lapat, Tagalog 


Steel point set in round wooden handle.  Handle has carved decoration, including word "Doring" and heart with arrow through it.;

Long reed shaft with a small section of fiber wrapped around the shaft near the pointed end. That end is hollow. The other end is solid. The point inserts into that end. 

The point is made of a section of reed cut in half lengthwise. One end is tapered to fit inside the shaft. The other end tapers to a point. The shaft of the point also tapers towards the end. 

The shaft and point are connected by a length of fiber cord.;

The metal arrowhead is triangular in shape. The base is V-shaped with a tang inserting into the wooden shaft.  The shaft is sharpened at the upper end and the tip is cut open to fit the arrowhead.  Fabric thread is tied to strengthen the shaft where the metal Is inserted.  

Feather is missing at the other end of the shaft, although remnants of them are still attached to the shaft. 

Rattan used to fasten the feather is still intact at the shaft's lower end. The very end is carved into a nock.;

The small arrowhead is hexagonal in shape. It's inserted into a wooden shaft. The shaft is composed of a shorter wooden foreshaft which is inserted into a longer bamboo shaft. Two ferrules of rattan are used to strengthen the parts where the metal arrowhead is inserted into the wooden shaft and the wooden shaft is inserted into the bamboo shaft.  

Fletching at the lower end of the rattan shaft is gone. 

Rattan ferrules coated with an unknown substance. The very end (proximal) is carved into a nock.;

Both ends of the bow are cut narrowed.  A small metal ring is fitted onto one end of the bow.  A sighting device is attached to approximately the middle of the bow with rattan. 

Bow has a slight curve. One side is flat, other rounded. The sighting device is a piece of carved wood with a nock-like ending. 

No bowstring.;

This is a string of beads made of seeds.  Oblong gray and light brown beads in sets of two to five alternate with pairs of round, black beads.  The beads are linked by a thin piece of cord. 


Possibly either Bontoc or Negrito 


These string of beads could also be used wrapped around the women's hair for ceremonies.;

One Igorote spear, modern copy, Ifugao tribe. 


Spear has a long wooden shaft, stained and polished black.  One end tapers down to a point onto which a long, roughly rectangular metal  point has been attached.  The base of the metal point is flat and wrapped around the tapered end of the wooden shaft. 


The other end has 3 woven rattan rings and a spiral of bamboo(?) or reed, stained red, around it.  The very tip has an open metal cylinder on it, like a cap, that covers a tapered end with a slit cut inside for B to attach and haft.;

Polearm.  Long wooden shaft, tapers toward the blade.  The other end is capped with a metal band and a round, metal, roughly conical band with a knob on the end.  The band has a hole through it.  Both ends of the shaft painted dark brown.   


Thinner fore-shaft hafted onto main shaft by a metal band with heart shaped and other carved designs.  On main shaft just before this band is a band of woven fiber covered with a red pigment.  Foreshaft has bands of similar woven fiber covered with red pigment and metal  bands. 


T-shaped metal blade hafted to foreshaft by a metal band.;

1 bow, quiver, and arrows.  Bow and quiver used by mountain tribes and captured from them, Dec 20, 1904 near Perud Cata.  The heads of the arrows are poisoned. 


Long quiver made of a segment of bamboo such that the natural node growth ring forms the closed base of the quiver container.  From the base, the adjoining segment of bamboo has been shaped such that a long, slightly curved blade-like portion extends downwards, tapering to a point -- ie most of the segment has been cut away, leaving a sliver. 


Incised designs in a band on exterior of the base.  Metal handle tied in place by lengths of rattan and woven rattan bands.  The rattan is covered in clear pigment/substance almost like lacquer.;

Section of an arrow.  Also see 92177b. 

Reed shaft with a small section of fiber wrapped around the shaft near the pointed end. That end is hollow, the other has a solid end. 

Point is detachable (92177) and inserts into the hollow opening.;
